description:
The Greedy Ape Heist is a deflationary collection of 6666 NFTs on the Solana Blockchain. Every Ape is completely unique! But not every Ape is here to stay…

Have you got what it takes to avoid ending up in THE SLAMMER?

The Slammer is where Apes end up when they get caught and removes them from circulation.

A portion of every secondary sale is added to The Slammer account and when there is a large enough amount, law enforcers roll through Solana marketplaces and lock up the cheapest Greedy Apes — “sweeping the floor.”

These Apes are taken out of circulation (“burned”), and the overall supply of Greedy Apes is reduced.

This is to reward diamond hand Ape hodlers by raising the floor price and reducing the supply, putting upward price pressure on all Greedy Ape NFTs. 

That's not all...

When you join the gang you will share a portion of the royalties. Every greedy ape you hold will grant you one share. The more you own the bigger your reward!

Are you ready to join the gang?

description:
Today, the globe connects in more profound ways than ever before. At a time when people may feel the most lost and alone, we are confronting the injustices that wear us down.
Being online in a global village makes the world that much smaller, allowing some people to connect on the issues that matter most. Being truly disconnected for the first time has pushed us to reconnect with renewed purpose.
Individuals rise to fight for racial justice, closing class disparities, LGBTQ+ acceptance, environmental justice, and human rights everywhere. This was the year to make a change. Problems that once were swept under the rug could no longer be ignored. The status quo was disrupted. Most lives changed overnight, and many people felt they had nothing left to lose. The fight for justice is universal where global populations see with more clarity the intersections of race, class, gender, geography, and sexual expression, and accept that oppressed people must unite and fight in solidarity in order to win.
The damages didn’t go unnoticed. The images reveal that the sacrifices made during these fights affected all those who seek justice. Though the world is not saved, and justice is not achieved overnight, it’s clear that the fire will burn on for years to come. Being alone forces us to confront our own biases. Distancing Together is a collection of photos that is premiering in collaboration with Scopio, and the following global artists: Andrii Omelnytskyi, Eric Yain Setten, Gerry Bueno, Giuseppe Lombardo, Gussy Lowenhielm, Jamiul Adnan, Marta Novikova, Mikhail Grebenshchikov, Nihal Raj, Roberto Juayan, Sergey Trush, Shrinkhla Srivastava, Steven Roe, Thomas Asteriades, Xavier Minguella Minguella, Артём Федоров
name: Distancing Together

description: The younger generation understands that, in the face of one of the greatest obstacles of time, they have a voice in the fight against systems that don't work for them. Many future leaders have been born, as great injustices increasingly are brought to light. They creatively find ways of expression through online and physical activism. The children in these images show us that there is a future worth fighting for. They show us that their generation deeply cares about the planet and all human life and that not much can stand in their way. They give hope. Future Leaders is a collection of photos that is premiering in collaboration with Scopio, and the following global artists: Alejandro Jaramillo, Alessandro Zarotti, Fernando Gonzalez-Criado Leyra, Giuseppe Lombardo, Haitham Dinnawi, Iris Savoy, Jason Little, Jason Segarra, Jun Pinzon, Laurentiu Vlad, Luca Votta, Martin Greene, Mougabé Saint Louis, Reinis Freilibs, Ruston Clyne, Simon Bond, Thomas Asteriades
name: Future Leaders

description: Our fights had a cost. All around the globe, the tragedies are both evident and subtle. Photos show the rubble, the hurt, the pollution, and the indescribable loss. We may not even know the full extent of these tragedies or even comprehend what has happened to others. It is important to remember that healing takes place, even when we are most weakened. These images remind us that no matter how bad the damages are that we sustain, there is always hope that we will come together again. Photography sheds light on the extent of the damages and attempts to capture the emotional cost. The Damages is a collection of photos that is premiering in collaboration with Scopio, and the following global artists: adel hwajre, Ain Media, Antoni Mantorski, arimacs wilander, Bruno Dias, Haitham Dinnawi, imam buhori ibe , Mario Scharff, Oke Oluwasegun, Rouzbeh Fouladi, Zeina Kassem
name: The Damages

description: A raised fist is a universal symbol of power, solidarity, and a desire for change. Our photographers capture this universal gesture all across the globe, in all different contexts, whether it is a fist raised for Black Power, for a cause unique to a community, or in celebration. The fist has become a symbol uniting people throughout the year in a universal language of strength and togetherness. Raise up! description: Having to be away from everyone else is bringing us so much closer. In our bubbles, we reinforce the bonds we already had and experiment with new ways of being together. description: If the COVID 19 pandemic had happened twenty years ago, what would have been different? There are many ways to answer that, but what stands out about this era is our expanded reliance on the virtual. Systems are crashing and are overloaded as usage suddenly skyrockets to previously unimaginable numbers. The images in this category show that whether you were a seasoned pro at freelancing from home, attending your first online class, or just figuring out how to call your grandkids using your computer, nobody could avoid what was inevitable. The idea of a complete shift to online communication was predicted to happen eventually, of course. Little did we know that over the course of this period we would all quickly become faithful citizens of the global online village and, well... CREATE A NEW WORLD! What is next? Today it seems as if many people are taken aback by just how much their lives are transforming, as normalcy quickly became irrelevant. Physical changes are apparent as everyone navigates life under lockdown. Masks hang right at the door along with the keys to our houses, friends stay six feet away, and being a homebody suddenly seems like the only way to be. Lockdown lifestyle was unexpected, but adaptation is a must. One of the biggest shocks that the pandemic brought most people is the necessity of social distancing, which tears many families and communities apart away from the socially connected life we knew into an unfamiliar form of isolation. For a lot of communities and cultures, this new way of
life is especially difficult to accept. Physical touch is a main form of communication, where love, respect, and acknowledgment are typically shown through simple gestures that have become taboo overnight. description: This is an ode to our heroes, all the professionals and volunteers working during the pandemic, and the ways in which we celebrate them. The essential workers are everyone’s heroes. When times get most uncertain, when it seems like life could be on the line, our hidden heroes do not stop. They make sacrifices, and they do it for the future of humanity. This pandemic may be one of the most defining battles of our generation, and it is a battle fought behind closed doors. Images can never fully capture all the ways our heroes fight. Yet even though their work often goes unnoticed, these heroes still carry on, as they do, as they will continue to do. Hidden Heroes is a collection of photos that is premiering in collaboration with Scopio, and the following global artists: Adel Hwajre, Akash Gayakwad, Alessandro  Castiglioni, Alex Gonzalez , Arimacs Wilander, Bernardo Ramonfaur, Bruno Dias, Dante  Diosina Jr, Egide Mbabazi, Hanny Hsian, Israel  Martínez Valdés, Jason Segarra, Jordan Scott, Lutfi Hanafi, Quiony Navarro, Xavier Minguella

description: Photos capture how things may have looked, but there are few ways to describe the eeriness of the abandoned places the world has been feeling, with widespread lockdowns and social distancing in full effect. Millions of people see what once were bustling squares, streets, and public spaces. They have become empty. Essential workers have put their lives at risk to serve the rest of the population. Can we stay home? Until all public spaces can safely be occupied again, emptiness is a reminder of how far the world is from returning to normalcy. description:
Although it was not the same for everyone, we all experienced isolation in the past few years. Everyday life as we knew it was completely transformed.
The images included in this part show the fear, the hesitation, even the excitement that this new way of life ushered in.  A lot of us picked up new hobbies at home and discovered interests we never knew we had as we felt more and more alone in our journeys.
These images are snapshots of inner workings. What was going on inside people’s heads? The collective trauma being experienced took its hold in unique ways. People showed their care for their loved ones in new ways. They mourned and grieved for those lost as well as for the lives they were missing out on.
The images that came pouring in from all around the world showed the array of locations, ages, genders, races, and classes that illustrated the vastness of the human experience. Although we were all far apart from one another, miraculously people found ways to stay more connected than ever.
We relied on one another in these dark times and used our latest tools to do so. The human tendency to stay together did not go away during the pandemic; it took on new shapes and forms. Isolation is a collection of photos that is premiering in collaboration with Scopio, and the following global artists: Albina Krasniqi, Aslı Gönen, David Rubin, Diana Samson, Evgenia Zhivaleva, Gairah Praskovia, Marcus Peña, Marta Novikova, Quiony Navarro, Siddharth Hirpara, Simone Martelli, Vikar Syed

description:
Our project is focused on the beauty of art and the possibilities offered by blockchain and Solana to discover, share, value, and exchange it. We have a long-term goal of building a community of both artists and collectors that can experiment with emotional art.
On this page, you can find some pieces of our previous collections and our recently launched: Psychoanalysis.
Psychoanalysis (new collection): 1100 pieces called "Psyches" and numbered from 1 to 1100. This collection has been generated using generative adversarial networks, mixing different styles and genres to create unique and unrepeatable artworks. We've been carefully selecting art pieces that follow some styles that interlink very well together: synthetic and analytic cubism predominantly and then other complementary styles with less influence on the outcome. We would like each piece to be used as a personal Rorschach test, where each owner is able to look at it and initiate an introspective process that brings him closer to discovering something meaningful.
